From this evidence it will be seen that insuranoe against losses and sickness can only in a narrow sense be regarded as a gild object. In the caseos a rich society, the relief offered might be sufficient to make membership desirable, but the richer societies charged heavier entrance and annual sees, so that presumably the poor could not enter. The poor societies that could give only a penny a day in charity to one, or a halfpenny to two needy brethren, offered no secure insuranoe to candidates for membership. The rule enjoining some small expenditure in charity seems rather then a part of the religious side of the gild work than a definite scheme for mutual in- suranco.
